'''''Facing the Giants''''' is an [[Cinema of the United States|American]] [[drama film]] released in
[[2006 in film|2006]]. It was directed by [[Alex Kendrick]] who also stars as its lead, Coach Grant Taylor. It is a classic underdog story about [[American football]].  Some of the characters in the movie confront conflict from [[Evangelicalism|evangelical Christian]] [[World view|world view]].

As typical of the genre, the coach and team are presented as facing impossible odds. The film is set in the southern [[United States]]. The team is part of a small Christian school, beset with its own set of problems. The school rallies around the team, and through struggles, tenacity and events beyond their control, all live happily ever after.

==Plot==
{{spoiler}}

Coach Grant Taylor at Shiloh Christian Academy has never had a winning football season. His car breaks down frequently, his house is falling down around him, and he and his wife are [[infertility|infertile]]. When he overhears school parents plotting to have him fired, he reaches a crisis point and prays. Reluctant at first, Coach Taylor resolves to get serious about his faith, and challenges his players to do the same. Events and situations work themselves out in a way that the entire school and community is touched, encouraged, and convinced that "with God, all things are possible."

The turning point for Coach Taylor is shortly after an intensive time of prayer. An old man who walks the halls of the school praying for the children shows up unexpectedly in the coach's office with a message of encouragement. The timing of that message overcomes the Coach's reluctance to change focus.

A sub-plot involves a short weak boy, David Childers (Bailey Cave), who hopes to play [[soccer]] despite the fact his school only offers football. His [[Paraplegia|paraplegic]] father encourages him to play football only as a kicker, and David is at first incredibly reluctant. David's best kick is barely 35 yards. In the end, David is called upon to kick a field goal 55 yards. His father (Steve Williams) tries to stand, holding onto a gate, and saying a small prayer. David kicks the ball high and a sudden, strong wind pushes the ball, making David score successfully and his team wins.

Another sub-plot involves a rebellious but talented transfer student, Matt Prater (James Blackwell). His father hopes for a football scholarship for his son, but the son constantly disrespects and disregards his father. After the entire school experiences a revival, Matt feels the need to address his father during the school day. Coach Taylor provides the needed ride to Matt's father's office, and Matt apologizes to his father for poor behavior. A business associate (David Nixon) of the boy's father then contributes, "I'd give my right arm to hear my son talk to me like that."

Interaction between assistant coaches Brady Owens (Tracy Goode) and J.T. Hawkins, Jr. (Chris Willis) provides comic relief, in contrast to stereotypical black/white strife in [[Dixie]]. Brooke Taylor's (Shannen Fields) wrestles with supporting her husband while facing continual disappointment in childbearing. This supplies both poignant and comedic moments.

{{spoiler-end}}

[[Mark Richt]], head football [[Head coach|coach]] at the [[University Of Georgia|University of Georgia]], makes a [[Cameo appearance|cameo]]. As presented in the film, Coach Taylor played under Richt at the University of Georgia.

=== Soundtrack ===
The film uses seven Christian pop songs from [[Third Day]], [[Casting Crowns]], [[Bebo Norman]], Ana Laura, Josh Bates and Mark Willard. There are five tracks of original score during the soundtrack.

Third Day's distributor is [[Provident Label Group]], which is associated with Provident Films, [[Sony]] and Samuel Goldwyn Pictures. The latter eventually distributed the film nationally. A routine request for permission lead to the national release of the film.<ref name=soundtrack/>

