==Production==
[[Image:Facing_the_giants3.jpg|thumb|left|Coach Taylor encourages the Eagles.]]
<!-- click on the image to see the image download page and associated fair use rationale. -->
Alex Kendrick teamed with his brother Stephen to write ''Facing the Giants''.  It is their second movie, the first being [[Flywheel (film)|''Flywheel'']]. The cast is comprised of volunteers from Sherwood [[Baptist]] Church, located in [[Albany, Georgia|Albany]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], as well as others from the surrounding area. The Kendricks hired five [[film crew|film professionals]] to fill the  technical positions on the motion picture. Church members and community volunteers helped to keep production costs down by supplementing the professional crew.

The Kendrick brothers' goal was to produce a family friendly movie that could be affordably shot in Albany, would be fun to watch, impactful to viewers, and glorifying to God. “I believe there is a huge culture of people who love movies, but leave theaters disappointed by films with profanity, immorality, and messages that trample their family’s values and faith,” said Stephen Kendrick. “''Facing the Giants'' is the type of movie we’ve been longing to see in the theater and own on DVD.”<ref>Unknown author (unknown date). [http://sherwoodpictures.com Production notes] for ''Facing the Giants'', Sherwood Pictures.</ref>

The movie was shot in [[High Definition video|high definition video]] and transferred to film.<ref>Unknown author (unknown date). {{imdb title|id=0805526|title=Facing the Giants}}</ref> Using real high school football teams, the football action sequences were shot by the film's [[Director of Photography|director of photography]], Bob Scott, who is a veteran [[cinematographer]] for [[NFL Films]]. Another [[NFL]] Films technician, [[Rob whitehurst|Rob Whitehurst]], recorded the movie's sound.

=== Promotion ===
The film was released in strategically-selected markets in a limited number of theaters.<ref>Unknown author ([[2007-01-30]]). [http://sherwoodpictures.com/templates/cusftg/details.asp?id=32007&PID=280806 Production notes,] Sherwood Pictures.</ref> According to the film's web site, the corporate sponsors of the music group Third Day became interested in the project after the request to use Third Day's music in the soundtrack.<ref name=soundtrack>Unknown author, ([[2007-01-30]]). [http://www.facingthegiants.com/dvdsoundtrack.php Soundtrack notes,] ''Facing the Giants'' web site.</ref>

==Reception==
=== Box office ===
According to the film's web site, it opened on 441 screens nationwide in the United States.<ref>Unknown (unknown). [http://www.facingthegiants.com ''Facing the Giants''] web site.</ref> Only three films in the top ten released that weekend grossed more per theater. Despite such a small number of theaters, the film opened in twelfth place. For such a small budget -- $100,000 -- the film has grossed over $10,000,000 as of [[2007-01-01]].<ref name=mojo>{{mojo title|id=facingthegiants|title=Facing the Giants}}</ref>

=== Reviews ===
Many critics felt the film was more evangelism than legitimate filmography. Those who found it acceptable noted the low budget and lack of professional talent, yet were impressed that amateur film makers could do so well in character development and dealing with difficult topics.<ref>Sounddude ([[2007-01-29]]). [http://www.rottentomatoes.com/vine/journal_view.php?journalid=160103&entryid=366968&view=public ''Facing the Giants'' review] at Rotten Tomatoes.</ref> Some reviewers even hint that Hollywood often doesn't do as well.<ref>Robert Butler (unknown date). [http://www.kansascity.com/mld/kansascity/entertainment/movies/15630372.htm| Inspiration from a solid team], ''Kansas City Star''.</ref>

For examples in the first category, Josh Rosenblatt wrote, "its feel-good storyline, shopworn message, and bottomless sermonizing would have played better in Sunday school than on the big screen, which is &mdash; let’s face it &mdash; Babylon’s turf."<ref>Josh Rosenblatt ([[2006-11-17]]). [http://www.austinchronicle.com/gbase/Calendar/Film?Film=oid%3a417777 ''Facing the Giants''], ''Austin Chronicle''.<!-- verified [[2007-01-29]]--></ref> Paul Doro wrote, "''Facing the Giants'' is a sermon much more than it is a movie. It jumps back and forth between football and various other subplots..."<ref>Paul Doro ([[2006-11-09]]). [http://www.jsonline.com/story/index.aspx?id=529185 First down, 110 trite minutes to go], ''Milwaukee Journal Sentinel''.<!-- verified [[2007-01-29]]--></ref>

Counter to the foregoing, "the script unfortunately devolves into cliche and cant, other aspects of the movie are quite good &mdash; so good, in fact, that ''Facing the Giants'' shames the efforts of a lot of better-financed moviemakers."<ref>Philip Martin ([[2006-09-29]]). [http://nwanews.com/story.php?paper=adg&section=MovieStyle&storyid=168158| Giants predictable but still good news],  ''Arkansas Democrat-Gazette''.<!-- verified [[2007-01-29]]--></ref> Also in favor of the film, "Here's a badly acted movie with a terrific story line that makes it well worth seeing.... Still, its 'all-volunteer' cast does not ruin its well-written, compelling script and believable dialogue."<ref>Linda Cook ([[2007-01-29]]). [http://www.rottentomatoes.com/click/movie-1166866/reviews.php?critic=columns&sortby=default&page=1&rid=1556743 ''Facing the Giants''], ''Quad City Times'', Davenport, Iowa.</ref>

Reviewers at Mojo<ref name=mojo/> give the film an A-.

===Rating controversy===
In May of 2006, the producers of ''Facing the Giants'' received notice from the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] ([[MPAA]]) that the film would be receiving a "Parental Guidance Suggested" rating, or "PG" [[MPAA film rating system|rating]].<ref name=abcnews>Unknown author ([[2006-06-22]]). [http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/story?id=2105871&page=1 Film Rating Upsets Christian Groups], ABC News.<!-- verified [[2007-01-30]] --></ref> One of the film's consultants, Mark Joseph, who had also conducted media strategy for films such as ''[[The Chronicles of Narnia]]'' and ''[[The Passion Of The Christ]]'' and had unsuccessfully lobbied [[Walden Media]] to release ''Giants'', crafted a media strategy to take advantage of the brewing controversy. He alerted ''[[The Drudge Report]]'' which picked up the story on [[2006-06-08]]. Within hours the story was a hot topic in religious and conservative media, outraging many who believed the MPAA was entering uncharted territory by allowing the religious content of a film to influence ratings decisions. In the ensuing days the story garnered media attention in countless media outlets like the ''New York Times, Good Morning America, Fox News'' and countless talk radio programs.<ref name=carmel>Unknown author ([[2006-06-23]]). [http://www.carmelentertainmentgroup.com/News/C15A8EF0-CC2F-4447-BD1B-E33F041A198C.html ''Facing the Giants'' MPAA Ratings Controversy], Carmel Entertainment Group.<!-- verified [[2007-01-30]] --> </ref>

According to the film's producers, they were originally told the motion picture received a "PG" rating because of its strong religious themes and because it elevated one religion over another.<ref name=abcnews/> <!-- Joan Graves, chair of the rating board, [Attribution not found. If source found, restore name.] --> The MPAA later countered that ''Facing the Giants'' contains football violence and also deals with the mature topics of infertility and depression, thus warranting the higher rating and initially denied that religious themes were an issue. <!-- Later, when producers of the film produced correspondence from the MPAA which backed up their claims, an MPAA spokesmen was forced to admit that religion was indeed a factor in the film's receiving a PG rating. [Source not found for preceding sentence, therefore edited out. Please return if reputable source found.] --> The producers claim the MPAA changed their story after the controversy began.<ref>Sam Hananel ([[2006-07-03]]). [http://ny.christianpost.com/article/culture/43/section/christian.movie%5Cs.rating.worries.lawmakers/1.htm Christian Movie's Rating Worries Lawmakers] ''Christian Post''.<!-- verified [[2007-01-30]] --></ref>

The MPAA, which oversees the rating board, received more than 15,000 e-mails within a week because of their decision and the media attention it drew, ten times more than they had ever received for any previous film.<ref>Peter T. Chattaway ([[2006-06-02]]). [http://filmchatblog.blogspot.com/2006/07/everyone-agrees-it-should-be-pg-movie.html Everyone agrees it should be a PG movie, but they can't agree on why...]] ''FilmChat''.<!-- verified [[2007-01-30]] --></ref>
 
Conversely, some Christian groups thought a "PG" rating might sway more teenagers into seeing ''Facing the Giants''. "I think that a 'G' for a lot of teenagers is the kiss of death," [[Focus on the Family]] media specialist Bob Waliszewski told the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. "(The PG rating is) a case where unfairness will probably be a blessing in disguise."<ref>Puzzanghera, Jim. ([[2006-06-21]]). Christians on Football Film: Give Us a G! ''The Los Angeles Times''. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2006/06/21/christian-groups-attack-h_n_23496.html Related summary] as the L.A. Times article is now archived.</ref> One report claimed the publicity garnered from the controversy was worth "about $8 million".<ref>Donna Miller ([[2006-11-09]]). [http://www.thecitizen.biz/index.php?id=2243 ''Facing the Giants'' in final week at Albany theater], ''The Citizen News''.<!-- verified [[2007-01-30]] --></ref>

The Kendrick brothers expected the "PG" rating because of the movie's mature themes and did not appeal the board's rating.<ref name=carmel/>

